result.execSummary:
The defendant Jason Allen Girtler was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Possession of Methamphetamine, a class I felony, Wisconsin Statutes 961.41(3g)(g).

Charge(s) in this case were read in to this or other case(s). A "read in" charge is a charge that is dismissed as part of a plea agreement, however:

  • The defendant agrees to have the court consider the charge(s) when sentencing for another crime, under Wis. Stats. 973.20(1g)(b); and
  • The defendant cannot be prosecuted for these charge(s) in the future.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

Attorney Joseph P Bastien V in court for Jason Allen Girtler. Defendant Jason Allen Girtler in court, in custody.  Attorney Abby Rockendorf in court for State of Wisconsin. Deputy Court Clerk: STW 
Case set Sentencing Hearing. Sentencing proceeded.  Statements by the State, defense and defendant. Negotiations placed on the record and confirmed by the parties. Court found the state has satisfied victims' rights law.

AS TO COUNT 1: The Court sentenced the defendant to serve a term of IMPRISONMENT of 21 MONTHS in the Wisconsin State Prisons, with credit for 125 days time served.  CONFINEMENT of 15 MONTHS and EXTENDED SUPERVISION of 6 MONTHS.  

The defendant is eligible for the Challenge Incarceration Program. The defendant is eligible for the Wisconsin Substance Abuse Program.  

The Court STAYED the sentence and placed the defendant on probation to the State Department of Corrections for a period of 2 YEARS.  

CONDITIONS OF PROBATION:
The Court ordered that all court costs, fees, surcharges (including the DNA surcharge) be paid through collection by the Department of Corrections and as a condition of probation/ extended supervision.  Any amount remaining due and owing is subject to civil judgment.
Provide a DNA sample for the Data Bank.
ABSOLUTE SOBRIETY.
AODA and other counseling needs to be determined; random urine screens.
Mental Health Assessment and comply with treatment. 
No new law violations rising to the level of probable cause. 
Seek and maintain employment.

The defendant is advised as a convicted felon he/she may not carry or possess any firearms/body armor.
The defendant is advised that voting rights are suspended during length of sentence.
The defendant is advised of his/her appeal rights by defense counsel.
